Having optimizing the above experimental conditions, the designed immunosensor based on the SWCNTs amplifier and peroxidase-like GQDs was treated with a gradient concentration of CEA. As shown in Fig. 6
                        , the responsive currents of SWV increase with increasing the concentrations of CEA in pH 8.5 PBS containing 2 mM H2O2 and 50 μM thionine. A linear response was obtained over the concentrations of CEA ranging from 50 pg mL−1 to 650 pg mL−1, and a low detection limit of 5.3 pg mL−1 was achieved (calculate based on 3σ/s). By comparing the performance of the designed electrochemical immunosensor with previously reported methods, and the limit of detection was comparable to many other immunosensors (Table 1
                        ). The high sensitivity of the designed immunosensor was probably due to the synergistic signal amplification of both rGO-AuNPs and SWCNTs-GQDs, as well as the strongly catalytic reaction towards H2O2.
